At the end of the trades, the Prague stock exchange fell into the negative
After Tuesday morning’s crash, the Prague stock exchange rectified its losses.
Trades with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, at the start of trading, the Prague stock exchange resumed its fall the day before, when it was losing almost six percent.
This time, the fall is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The market reaction to the result of the vote in the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan for the U.S. financial sector, is thus also noticeable among us.
Falling shares in Asia
Asian stocks fell sharply on Tuesday, even though the indexes succeeded in clearing some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hang Seng Index of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost four percent during trading, but later wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the Chinese stock movement of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent as markets closed in Shanghai.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange were losing more than five percent, but eventually we managed to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"Hesitation about the U.S. bailout will affect financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The bloodbath of U.S. stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the proposed financial system support, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (almost K<0xC4><0x8D> 12 trillion).
Legislators thus deny the call for support for President George Bush’s project.
According to Bush, the project should address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks on Monday suffered a bloodbath and major stock indices experienced their biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a drop of such magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress Gives Up: U.S. Government Can Inject $700 Billion Into Banks
The leaders of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial aid to the US financial system.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers took a decisive turn in talks on the adoption of a bailout in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, success is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to a vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, the chairman of the House banking and financial regulation committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, by Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to a vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be a major first psychological factor to revive financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan needs to be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have resolved our divergent views on the form that the package of measures for market stabilization should take," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi.
According to her, the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, lawmakers met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the bottom of the government a final form.
The latter should buy back from financial corporations the unsold real estate assets that cause financial firms to lose considerable amounts and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to pursue this market recovery plan, but I think we are there," says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling equity markets.
Democrat Senator Harry Reid says lawmakers are pushing for a final deal in Congress as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors ahead of the start of trading in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the Congressional decision could influence Monday’s trading.
For the time being, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will vote, or whether the negotiations will remain blocked at the last moment by this or that problem.
Legislators hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system should be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be made available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility of blocking the granting of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomed the progress in the negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of putting it in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Sen. Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on accountability for the financial program, protection of taxpayers from losses, the relief agreement, the time-line plan.
The new law also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and it establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides aid for homeowners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new down payments in the case of mortgages it will buy back, while reducing debtors' monthly payments and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that it is not known what the mechanism and price of the purchase of the problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is not, according to Marek, so important.
“It’s much more important that the congressmen agree, this week, that they support this plan and that they will dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time," Marek said.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same goes for music on the go, i.e. compressed music, to put it simply - MP3 music.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time supporting headphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobile phones.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and sending SMS, it is able to play music and movies, record them, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Given that no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are virtually witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The more functions you use, the shorter the interval between two reloads.
And playing music is one of the most important inflows of energy.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases, this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get yourself, to be sure, a second charger for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
This problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of a recharge, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
It is obviously possible to record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
When it comes to drives, you don't need, except for the iPod, any software.
Simply fill in the music device from the computer via the USB connector.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library themselves, categorized according to the performer's name, the album title, the style, or the user's judgment.
Some devices display only one index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, pay particular attention to the life of the battery, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it that for a limited time, for example taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3.
Virtually all mobile phones are capable of this today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
Everyone can play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also manage to play music in WMA format.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), on the other hand, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding operator’s (or another provider’s) web pages from your mobile phone and purchase the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical motive.
The supply of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to radio tubes quickly made.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile phones on themselves.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have earphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which practically all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three or four thousand crowns, you can have an already very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy control.
Really anyone manages to command the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest ones (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the control to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive get away with even 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of the control is similar to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobile phones have the same user menu as separately sold MP3 players, is the one that has gone the farthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
- Maybe.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission' s final steps in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, made a chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently no longer very lucky (in fact, now it would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which conventional operators had to subsequently react.
Yet, even before the arrival of troublemakers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Great Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could be a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in Czechia, among others.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators look like low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity move.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“True men choose Mobilking — an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work also at home.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of enterprise customers, has not hidden, for long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to make progress in the negotiations," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“Right now, we do not believe there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of Telefonika O2's press department in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet recorded a viable and bilaterally advantageous project that could serve as a basis."
“It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time, we should have a concrete agreement now."
Instead, Vodafone is focusing on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared fees and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most contributions from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating the emergence of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to understand themselves as thieves in fairs. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, at the time of the creation of the U:fon, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s web pages.
Nowadays, the U:fon lends itself as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: “Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at this time, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS Department of External Relations in response to our question.
Such a statement would not be surprising on the part of representatives of operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one profits from its position in the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially as Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile phone services."
However, pressure for an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all gas stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of the competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and consequently none has an increased corresponding responsibility for its behaviour in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even the telecoms regulator," Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant market position is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator logically has a monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Putting the responsibility back on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in communications, by means of which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the novelization of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not achieved, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This the representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know very well, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one's watching, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone price lists, but these are only partly public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Customized mobile phone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure of a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you are talking about were to happen, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would be looking at and that could result in an end to the collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the heads of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, speaks out against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible benefits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question arises at <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators sometimes tried more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies have intervened in the developed countries, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up with the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators treat this issue like a hot potato that you get rid of by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But don't throw the sleeve after the blow.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear with us, the Czech mobile market may be back on track.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will hardly be able to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
