Sudetenland demands a referendum in the United States
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that <0xC5><0xA0>umava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna (South Bohemian Scientific Library).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jiho<0xC4><0x8D>eská v<0xC4><0x9B>decká knihovna.
Germans from <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> Krumlov begged the American president in the letter not to allow "<0xC5><0xA1>umavská <0xC5><0xBE>upa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter, signed "People, whom the fate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava is at heart," reads.
Given that the rally in Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, inconsiderate attitude, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take in his hands the protectorate of the <0xC5><0xA0>umava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state alien to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter reads.
The alleged reason the authors cannot sign the letter is fear of the desire for revenge of the “Czech oppressors”.
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of <0xC5><0xA0>umava, he would have only to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat na<0xC3><0xAF>ve, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Germans of the Sudetenland of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Britain to gain some sort of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of <0xC4><0x8C>eské Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein region capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would be profitable to them," Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
