Questions that arise after the accident: Are stewards in the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance bus is forbidden
In the context of the tragic bus accident of the Student Agency company near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can move inside the bus during the journey.
"If the law is to be strictly and formally respected, the activity of a steward is contrary to the road traffic law," said Transport Ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck who crossed paths with the coach.
The girl was unfortunately seated next to the driver in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the bus can have an accident or even brake abruptly, even when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is under its data sheet equipped with standing or not seats.
If this seating equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing seats; this was confirmed in Aktuáln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz by the director of the company Radim Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura.
“This is an issue that we have dealt with with the ministry and, at the beginning, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they cancelled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet on the way as long as they have their own seats," he said.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no unequivocal legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescription deals with this role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement prohibits the carrier from offering services.
The road transport law knows only the term vehicle receiver; it does not define its rights and duties," added spokesperson Hanzelka more ambiguously.
Josef Pokorn<0xC3><0xBD>, the director of the Department of Road Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law deals sufficiently with the issue.
"It all depends on whether the coach has in its approval the permission to propose standing seats.
It's all in there," he said.
The coaches are divided into urban, where there are standing seats and a limited maximum speed, long distance coaches with standing seats and a higher permitted speed and long distance coaches without standing seats with the highest permitted maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Just like on a plane, an expert says.
Jaroslav Ho<0xC5><0x99>ín, an expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) on transport safety, does not see the displacement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service in aircraft.
Neither is it certain when turbulence will occur and the flight attendant may hit her head.”
In the event that the bus braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
Same way as in an urban bus or in a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of the stewards by internal prescriptions," he said, adding that from the point of view of the law, the issue is not resolved.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only bus carrier to offer the services of stewards.
He hired two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their occupation to be a hazardous occupation.
"Nevertheless, as soon as I have the impression that it is a risky trade, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper on board.
It would also reduce costs," he said.
The safety concern is the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles by the director of the Asian Alexei Litvine, which ensures, compared to SA, a very small number of lines.
"We have no hostesses, we have opposed them from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident," he told T<0xC3><0xBD>den.cz a year ago.
A huge tragedy has happened
A young hostess from the Plze<0xC5><0x88> region, who had been working for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using a blinker and blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter trying to avoid it by means of a sudden maneuver, but he neared it by his right side.
Jan<0xC4><0x8D>ura refuses that the two seats reserved for the rest of the stewards have been sold.
"In the case of long distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company plans to file a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the family of the girl, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but with regard to the financial compensation, it also counts on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been in the works for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transportation, could clarify the trips of the stewards on board the coach.
"Now, it has not reached any conclusion on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of the mobile phone at the wheel," says expert Ho<0xC5><0x99>ín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally jeopardize the safety of passengers," said spokesman Hanzelka, adding that the control of the safety of coaches is under the control of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
The hopes of the Düsseldorfers rest on Frankfurt.
There was no shortage of words in the letter from the WestLB Steering Committee to the employees of the house.
Through a merger of the entities of the Düsseldorf financial institute with the Frankfurt Deka-Bank, "the central financial market institution of the financial group of the Sparkasse" could be constituted, according to the letter made public on Monday.
The WestLB would bring a "block of competence" coupled with sustainable productivity in such a case.
All in all, such a relationship could be the decisive start to other concentrations in the banking sector in the Länder.
This is what it looks like when a steering committee wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because the WestLB, injured, is still under heavy pressure.
It was not only the European Commission, but also the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority that, only recently, made it clear to the Government of the Land of North Rhine-Westphalia that time was running out in the search for a future solution.
For some time now, however, there has been talk - also on the Frankfurt side - of a relationship of some kind between the bank Deka, which knows the clients of the Sparkasse by their investment funds, and the WestLB.
Certainly the head of the Deta-Bank Franz Waas made known during the presentation of the figures of the semester at the end of August that he saw no meaning in the merger of the house of the Mainzer Landstrasse with a bank of Land, whether it be the Helaba or the WestLB.
However, the Board of Directors of the Deka, each half of which is supported by the banks of the Länder and by the groupings of savings banks, has instructed the Steering Committee to conduct talks with the WestLB with a view to joint commercial activities.
It could then be the debit of the financial market, or parts of it.
The talks, however, have only just begun, it is said in the financial square.
This is not the first time that Deta-Bank, which with its 3,000 employees is one of the largest employers in Frankfurt's financial centre, has come into play when it comes to consolidating the savings bank sector.
In 2003 it was believed for a time that the Deta-Bank could merge with the Bank of the Rhineland Palatinate and Halbab.
Yet nothing came out of this ternary bouquet.
As soon as the plans had been made public, the government of the Land of Hesse ruled against any participation of Hellaba in them.
Later, the other two houses did not join either.
The Bank of the Land of Rhineland Palatinate has been attached instead to the Bank of the Land of Baden-Württemberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been new negotiations on the regrouping of the Deka-Bank with the banks of the Länder.
Lastly, however, Günther Merl, chairman of the board of Hellaba, had spoken out against any merger business strategy with his bank.
Notwithstanding this, the feeling seems to be spreading that the grouping of the different institutions of the public sector is particularly urgent.
Now that the Bavarian state parliamentary election has passed, a union of the BayernLB with the Baden-Württemberg state bank could come to fruition in the first place.
For the Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure for new mergers were to increase, the potential partners would gradually escape it.
In the South, it would now be a junior partner, although it has so far withstood the crisis better than the banks of Munich and Stuttgart.
The Hesse-Thuringen Savings and Transfers Group, which owns 85 percent of Helaba's capital, locked in any union with the WestLB at the beginning of the year.
The NordLB would remain strict.
Such geo-strategic reflections, however, reflect only one of the facets.
Another aspect raises the question of how the different business models of each of these banks can match.
In June, Merl stated that the decisive question of which business model the future capacity of the Länder banks should be secured had not so far been resolved by the German grouping of savings and transfer funds.
In the long run, a shredding of the WestLb could take place, a shredding which is obviously not desired here.
This is also what is mentioned in the letter of the steering committee in place: in any case, a "global solution" for the establishment would be aimed at.
How all this will be put in the same basket with the union of certain entities with the Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
