Nights of insomnia for shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word ‘relatively’ and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This indeed happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, is getting a billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are being issued up to 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes as much from private banks as from publicly owned banks.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which has not been possible since because of mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced by 95 per cent to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.37 million, while the equity rate had also decreased slightly by 1.6 to 1.45 per cent.
Ongoing and net profits from financial transactions fell to zero compared with the same period last year, profits from the allocation of receivables and determined securities and the termination of provisions in credit operations fell by more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it is only thanks to the significant profits from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for the Konzern companies that the gains deficit of about 16 percent was found to be moderate.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially speculated poorly on industrial real estate loans, which had then been subsidized to the bank Aareal.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then became more intensively involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private investors and the state (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations that should have on the calculation of the gains and losses of the group an essential material effect that still remains rather vague.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had already been truncated to two-thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has been a major state and infrastructure investor since the acquisition of Depfa.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing in the inter-bank market as it has no client deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has once again dried up considerably, as banks have accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs part of the total loans of the Depfa for a short-term refinancing facility each year – about <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>50 billion.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s financing need is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of business at present.
Other sources say the refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Chairman Georg Funke explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to the medium-term financial markets.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Services Surveillance Establishment (Bafin) assume that the market capacity of the Hypo Real Group is now assured.
The shareholders and creditors of the bank have only to hope for this.
However, given the dynamics and impossibility of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest press releases, still at the gates of insolvency Sunday evening, this bailout at least provisional will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price collapsed 75 percent to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.30.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While debts in the first place have barely moved, the prices of secondary loans are declining.
The most affected are the investment funds of the former daughter company Württemberg Hypo and of course those that have a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of the Hypo Real Estate bank seemed to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be considered as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the sharpening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the same institute that brought the crisis into the institution by the purchase of the bank Depfa.
As long as issuing institutions, governments and less-affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, a resorption of arrears can be assumed over time.
Or what no one dares to hope for right now – that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of renewed rumors of partial nationalization, the likelihood that was approaching certainty has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia above all to long-term creditors on the decision whether they should part with their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn on to carry forward losses for the next few years on the next capital income tax of automatically drawn stock gains.
