Rats have feelings too.
A rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean it also feels fear?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as us?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and approach the questions of feeling or in general of consciousness, we enter into hard-to-reach terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees, or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At the very least, then, for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them the awareness of who we are, and the ability to foresee and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity might lie in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses us great problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without regard to their contents, and this is exactly what happened in studies of primate short-term memory, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of the visualization.
But what does this mean for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its aftermath, such as the reactions of the body) takes over from the vivid memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volatile nature, arise, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities arise in the body sensation regions of the cortex and brainstem, just as Jaak Pankseep does, however, focus more on the brainstem.
As this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could quite participate in cross-sectional sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe this is indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in men and rats is likely to be felt as fear in both cases: how, however, could one check whether rats and men feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if it feels afraid?
In my view, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Certainly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain stems, but cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem causing sensations?
And even if we could prove it for humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are likely to differ completely from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is made on the nervous plane to the extent that the same thing is measured in rats and in humans.
As I do not explore the language and consciousness in rats, nor the sensations, I do not know if they exist.
We could judge this as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly bump myself against a wall.
I am a pragmatic emotionalist.
