A Dark Street in the City, Often Forgotten, and May Soon Be For Sale.
New York has hundreds of avenues, boulevards, streets and other parallel roads, some famous, others only functional.
And even some veteran taxis as well as long-time local residents don't know how to give directions to get to Extra Place, as they have never heard of it.
The street lies in East Village and runs north of First Street—not to be confused with Second Street—between Bowery and Second Avenue.
About 30 feet wide by 120 long, it resembles a dusty driveway rather than an active artery.
. No signs indicate the street.
It is virtually impossible to find it on a standard atlas.
This street has admirers.
For example, there is Avalon Bay, the builder of the recent luxury buildings on First Street.
He would like to feed Extra Place, and create a more seamless passage to the stores and boutiques, which should open in the new buildings.
Other admirers, including longtime neighbors, said they were charmed by this shortcut simply because it remains one of the last and oldest streets in the block.
But the Department of Preservation and Real Estate Development of the city that manages the street, has no interest in keeping it.
This month, at a meeting of neighborhood landlord committees, representatives from the city agency and Avalon Bay drafted a proposal authorizing the building builder to buy the street.
But the committee prefers that the street remains in the hands of the city, and has asked for a new proposal to be submitted next month, said Susan Stetzer, the local manager of the Committee No. 3.
"There are only a few spaces left in the city, and we would like the city to keep Extra Place," she said.
“They could offer to rehabilitate it and manage it, which Avalon could do, but we want to keep it public.”
Avalon Bay announced several months ago that it wanted to feed the small street and install seats, some of which would be used by a café to which the builder would grant space.
The proposal for this potential acquisition was made public at this month’s meeting.
Michele de Milly, spokesperson for Avalon Bay, said that although the company wants to exploit the street, that doesn’t necessarily mean it wants to own it.
“Avalon Bay’s main interest is to re-make this abandoned driveway, and make it public,” she said, noting that it was the city that suggested the sale.
Seth Donlin, a spokesperson for Real Estate Preservation, confirmed that the city wanted to sell the street, stressing further that the agency’s mission was to develop the property rather than manage it.
Compared to its more colorful neighbor, Bowery, Extra Place has left a slight historical footprint.
Some believe that Extra Place bears this name since 1802, when the inheritance of Philip Minthorne's many children's large farm was divided, leaving aside this small piece of land, which has since remained abandoned.
The back entrance to the CBGB, a punk rock monument closed in 2006, has reopened at Extra Place; the street is certainly more famous thanks to the cover photo of the Ramones album Rocket to Russia.
“This place was beautiful,” said Danny Fields, the Ramones’ manager, who took the picture in November 1976.
It was full of scrap metal, rags, barrels, posters, leaves and ropes."
Some residents, including bloggers who had previously talked about the East Village’s evolution to luxury, objected to the idea of selling Extra Place, saying this humble little property should remain public.
Others have proclaimed Extra Place as a true rarity--a fragment virtually identical to the city that should be put away in peace.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled "The Book of Disputes: A Bitterly Nostalgic Look at a City in the Extinction Process") tells the story of the City and Extra Place, published in 1952 in The New Yorker.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac, dark by day and night, and bounded by the doors of a rusty iron warehouse and shutters, full of newspapers from the past week flying along the gutters."
With few exceptions, the street always looks the same.
A rat runs agile at the bottom of the alley, near a door that once led to the CBGB, and has now become the headquarters of a chic clothing store.
Graffiti on the walls, an empty 22-ounce bottle of beer, sits next to newspapers that have just been thrown away.
A few passers-by said they rarely think of Extra Place, and suggested its enhancement.
Field, on the other hand, said he believed some subordinates felt the appeal of the street in its current state.
“The best years of my life,” he said, “have taken place in dark, wet, and disgusting places.”
The Bilingual Debate: Immersion in the English Language
In this part of the Education Supervision program, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss candidates' positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a former California studies fellow and former director of the education department at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Thought. Why Middle Classes Must Be Able to Choose Their School."
Attracting the favors of Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are an interesting example of this.
Obama’s campaign points out that “Afro-American and Latino students are less likely to graduate than white students.”
To combat these differences, Mr. Obama's education program supports, among many other topics, "bilingual transitional education" for those learning English.
However, the question that arises for Obama is whether his desire to achieve bilingual education that defends classroom instruction in languages other than English, goes beyond his interest in eliminating differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The majority of the students at this school are Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of students, consisting of many newcomers, study English.
Among CM1 students, 100% passed the 2008 state maths exam, expert level.
Similarly, almost 93% of students passed the English-language-arts exam
This incredible success was achieved thanks to another ingredient than the one proposed by Mr. Obama.
Sixth Street relies on analysis, practice, a constant assessment of capabilities and an exemplary attitude.
In addition, and here is an example that Mr. Obama could copy, reports Linda Mikels, principal of Sixth Street, this school has established the instruction of the English language "full immersion".
Total immersion in the English language focuses on the almost constant use of English in instruction.
Ms. Mikels, opposed to bilingual education, told me "we had a huge success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, 12 months later, if you went without his class, you would not have had any chance to identify him."
"It works," she observes, "it worked for us."
Shouldn’t Obama take the example of the Sixth Street Prep and replicate it in other schools that are mostly Hispanic students learning English?
The excellent results achieved by this school speak for themselves; but the policies on education within its party (the Associations for National Education have long supported bilingual education) and its enormous support for bilingual education, obscure the prognosis of Mr. Obama's response.
Although he is in favour of the fact that immigrants learn English, Mr. Obama recently regarded this issue as insignificant, when he proclaimed that we must all stop polemicizing on the wording of laws in the English language.
"On the contrary," he said, "you have to make sure that your child speaks Spanish."
If Mr. Obama really wants to eliminate the differences, then he should look carefully at the models of education that work, rather than scorn them or view them as insignificant.
