In a City Apart, Pride and the Trials of Dark Life
Hidden in the development of its huge park, a few miles from the sunny, bright and giant Orlando, is a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, the first all-black city to integrate, Zora Neale Hurston's childhood home, this description she made in 1935, is no longer so simple to make nowadays." The city with five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of guavas, two schools and no prison."
It has now become a city of pilgrimage
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the Zora Festival held every year in Eatonville to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in a variety of ways, the city she describes- has become touristy thanks to its inclusion in the Florida tour guide published by The Depression- era Federal Writers' Project- remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was already in the 1930s, when Hurston recounted that the rural black population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knows us so little, doesn't know what he's losing."
Although this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who invoked an open dialogue on the theme of race, many here remain cautious of the foreign eye.
"We are very careful about how to tell the story," said Hortense Jones, 59, a long-time resident and the city's oldest parishioner.
"It has to be in line with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and fighting.
It represents both a historical model of black power takeover and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a central point but also an example of southern black rural culture - sometimes disdained, sometimes acclaimed - that recalls the birth of American slavery.
Which would explain why residents are both proud and protective.
The interest in the image of Eatonville born with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through sincere, dialect-filled books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed this city, located just off Route 17, a road that runs through often-forgotten central Florida, ending in a chapter of black history and human drama.
Bold as a big box in life as in literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was later divided into several private parts.
“After crossing the road on the left,” she writes, “you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its well-preserved gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller has always taken care of, although he can barely read and write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds as well as anything that can be used by people passing by.
So, in barely a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government but also illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn’t really a portrait that everyone liked.
Zora described the reality well," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls that Hurston immortalized, quoting the colorless songs performed by men who praised their beauty.
She added: "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered as a lively and eccentric person, who frequently returned after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in the city without warning, aboard a big Chevrolet, a cigarette in his mouth and wore pants here, where even today, we are proud of traditional clothes.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many made fun of her.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” he said.
But he adds further, swinging in his chair from the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was certainly baptized, that "she never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten it.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in any grave in Fort Pierce, Fla, where she lived.
In Eatonville, no big commemoration, no plaque for the general public.
I don’t think they understood the contribution or legacy she offered to the world,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a Hurston biography published in 2003.
A crucial moment occurred in the 1980s.
Officials in Orange County wanted a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's two-lane main street.
The development of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal was made as Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among many other things, put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the race-mixing dispute drove hatred to the gates of the community.
“At that time, a bunch of young white people were throwing oranges or objects at people sitting on the side,” Franklin said.
"A lady has even died."
They threw a watermelon out of their car.”
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court’s request for forced integration, defining his decision in Brown v. Board of Education as “insulting rather than glorifying my race.”
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, while positive in some respects, has diluted Eatonville's cohesion and weakened youth confidence.
