Civil rights, moreover, have created space for many other Zora Neale Hurston--black writers, actors, and artists who have gone beyond prejudice, such as her, armed with joyful self-confidence and guidelines such as, "How can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!"
It's beyond me."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited Hurston’s anonymous grave and began to struggle to revive her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, a true bestseller, reintroduced it to the American canons.
The highway project came just as Eatonville’s most famous girl had regained her appeal.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors consider her a savior.
The community began organizing a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences of the highway.
Hundreds of fans came to the festival’s opening two years later, and many return in January to commemorate it.
After many years, the county rejected the proposal of the highway.
"The fiasco of the five-lane motorway, extremely fast, a real civic pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd summed it up by stating that "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents were beginning to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been listed as a historic city since 1998.
A monothematic library (renamed Hurston) opened in 2006, on a beautiful Kennedy Boulevard, rebuilt.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time consider itself a back street on a summer rainy day, small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, there are 90 percent of blacks.)
Foreigners who come to discover the history of Eatonville, its raison d'être, are still treated with caution.
Permission must be sought for most interviews, and certain things--such as the walls of the old church in Eatonville, painted by the white man, illustrating black men in the fields--should not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a courageous teacher who has a weakness for bright red, are still afraid that their island community will be well understood.
