In 1997, Bauer began a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, recall classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing per se, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are among the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of collection of portraits exhibited in the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a more or less long moment.
I believe that in photography portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you do not know or that leave you only a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I still try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at number 20 rue de la Mata (parallel street to the Hercules People's Square) which will be open until October 16th.
