Alcohol drivers will have to install the ‘alcolock’ system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative sanctions for blood alcohol, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents starting the vehicle in a state of intoxication, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered as a pilot project that will last a year.
Its purpose is the reintegration of the driver by offering road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety but also the General Directorate of Road Safety and the Foundation Technological Institute for Automobile Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a state of intoxication, take back the car.
The alcoholock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow forward; or when the driver's level of alcohol is higher than the authorized level.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is at the expense of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of infractions during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people each year.
This only applies to administrative penalties for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, the reform made by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some commercial and function vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install in school buses this system as it has been done in France.
