The Interview - Blood Became Safe Again
Héma-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained the public’s confidence that had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the public's grumbling, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not occur again.
While Judge Krever was delayed in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and the two territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Thanks to efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground in the years that followed, we have regained the public's confidence," she said, before proudly stating that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were erupting in Europe, says the one that has held the fort since its founding in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when this is not known and serious illness can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, blood was refused to those who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Now, a few years ago, it was demonstrated beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which make it possible to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have helped shorten the silent period, which extends from the time the person was infected to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors may become infected unknowingly and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in every 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain health," says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary, noting that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
“The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to be recharged with red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which on average includes only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood.
Any healthy person 18 years of age and older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
“Today’s life is so unbridled, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago the bankruptcy of our 1,000th cord blood sample and we plan to collect more than 1,000 per year.
We should start proposing it for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
