Free Opinion - The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Barrick Gold Mining.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a defamation suit of six million against three authors and a small publisher without a penny in order to launch a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frighten anyone who dares to look into the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally held through the exchange of ideas and not with batons.
It was therefore enough for the mine to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the financing of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both call for a "public" debate while scorning the opinions of that same public?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers only to the well-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag lawsuit (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a notice against the authors of Noir Canada urging them to cease the use of this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s prosecution is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to be quoted from credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate prosecution makes it clear that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for academia, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of control over the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news just minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress toward an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done in a way that protects the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: If we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that would cause a new failure on the mood of investors.
The time limit we agreed was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election have been rather favorable to the agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction that we are forced to reach this extreme.
Democrat Senator Barack Obama has added some provisions to the deal, including one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and one on the salaries of the heads of state-rescued businesses.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on U.S. television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, responded: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The broad outlines I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to digest and we’re going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayer money the dubious, risky and unsold assets of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprimes) before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the slump of banks and institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who overturned the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that they have come out of this impasse since the Democrats accepted that some “toxic” assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to incur losses for five years under this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for a first tranche of $250 billion to be added to another $100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The additional $350 billion should be approved by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will be worth dividends in the event of a profit and that it can resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the seizure procedures for dwellings attached to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as setting limits on the remuneration and severance pay paid to the executives of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote of the House of Representatives as of today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
Yesterday, in fact, votes continued to rise against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that benefits taxpayers.”
Host of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics," Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: we ask Congress not to rush and to carefully consider the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three countries of Benelux announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was renounced to acquire its competitor in the middle of a shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and 10 largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, one recovers a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It’s just something that savers and households appreciate now that times are uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalising another bank that had been battered by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all the loans in progress at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than $41 billion (US $75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
His beauty in the eyes of azure was for a long time his asset card, some will say his weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent that flowed from the source will also have him away from the register of power that gives birth to the true sacred monsters.
What a great runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer at his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a sort of rival on the screen, more cautious in his game, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of the freedom and breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often makes beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother of origin.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, ultimate mark of quality.
For in him was projected a whole country in love with the self made man, the war fighter of the Pacific, wounded in combat, who in the early 50s studied dramatic art at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio of New York, before triumphing in the theater, in television, soon in the cinema.
The same man who campaigned for civil rights was also the car driver who ranked second at the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 1979, paired with a sex symbol, although he was a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
Also disappear with him the shadowy areas of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the splinters of show-business, of which we will not have completely pierced the enigma.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The disappearance of Paul Newman caused dizziness to moviegoers this weekend, as his big roles clash on the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of ever-changing American seventh art parades through it.
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on a Hot Roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all his promises.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, reprised after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic villain in the brilliant The Sting (The Scam), Oscar for best film in 1973.
A bitter billiard player and avenger in Robert Rossen's magnificent The Hustler (1961), he will reprise the character on the return in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him in 1987 his only Oscar out of nine nominations.
That face through the ages, it was him.
He's back.
The times are moving through his path.
The young people know him mainly through the cult Slap Shot of George Roy Hill (1977), in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen brothers.
With a final role as a godfather of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the loop was closed.
Against several film legends who left the profession early, Newman will have remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its golds, its splendors and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "as a living challenge to "underplaying" judging its performances too supported.
The profession was not always tender for the handsome Paul Newman, to whom the roles fell for a long time.
He played, however, less often the young first than the marginals: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect features reflected the drifts and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known facets of his true pudic sensibility.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (after the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, traced a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He who lost his son Scott to an overdose dedicated to him his film Harry and Son in 1984, work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rain of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very saddened: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the disappeared actor.
Beyond his legendary career, he is also a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the Hollywood drifts.
We will have seen many of his benette sit on jars of dressing, sauces, cookies and other foods, judging the process of quite bad taste, although gag at first.
The profits from these sales were nonetheless paid to his Foundation for Children in Trouble.
Newman, instead of sitting on his myth, will be committed to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these phrases: "Always and until the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
