And a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a lucid and generous American artist.
Model citizen, in sum and in addition.
What could Zuschlag & amp; Company manufacture in their invoice factory?
Hearings on the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will soon begin on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damages. Other charges have been indicted against them, such as falsehood and use of falsehoods.
According to the prosecution, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand into the pockets of some people.
Their method, which was also made public by the investigating authorities, was to get the money from the grants obtained by issuing expense bills, behind which no real benefit was provided and thus, the associations never met their commitments.
According to the indictment, much of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they procured invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, this was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the deposition of the latter, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they realized the other invoices that they were going to introduce, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation, which would later be known as Együtt a Harmadik Evezredert, was full of errors in form and substance.
A guest house, located in Badacsonytomaj, had in reality only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there. However, the invoice mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
Invoice issuers with an overwhelming imagination also fell into excess when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért nor that of the Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor's office.
Gy<0xC5><0x91>z<0xC5><0x91> Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew right away that they were fake documents.
“Our company name and our tax number were placed in the wrong place on the stamp.”
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the invoice, a hundred people had stayed there, also did not fit, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have so much room.
