The issuers of zealous invoices also did not inquire about the Budapest travel agencies, being part of their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which is also contrary to the accounting practices of the agency.
In addition, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up on behalf of the Hotel Révfülöp on the order of Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért was incorrect, since the services of the company do not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, the employees of the hotel only issue printed invoices, while the false handwritten invoices were repaid.
The prosecution's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes in mentioning the carriage of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was the investment advisory.
In addition, it was also for defects of forms, such as inadequate invoice types and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredert Alapítvány, of XXI.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó sports camp, which both deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
The counterfeiters also did not pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time when (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Invoices deliberately established
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were required to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták group, has issued an invoice to the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of HUF 4 million.
