The Psychology of Overbidding: Why Are We Spending More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was playing the lottery, while the other group was taking part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) process, the researchers were analyzing the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the over bid of a third, the whole being under the brainstem, called the striatum, began to move intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight in front of the violent striatum reaction.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
During these, three groups overbid a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received that $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was on one on victory, while on the other on failure.
Proving the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for the victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor in the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
There are an estimated one hundred thousand patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are receiving treatment, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases engendered differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach ache and nausea.
Then a visible jaundice develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stool becomes lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not aware of the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneakly destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
There are currently 200 million people with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating doctor immediately upon the observation of symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would already have contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing to what extent belief in God could influence the pain tolerance of the human being.
As part of this at least bizarre experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
