The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking at either religious-themed or more general-themed painting.
The Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary they felt like “safe,” like someone who is “cared for” and they “called down, and peace invaded them.”
In view of the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the experiment himself, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
"We should find an image that they react to very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
