Smart Car Imitates the Flight of the Bumblebee
What better way to develop barrier-avoiding technologies than by imitating an existing barrier detector in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the starting strategic idea, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robot control system, type BR23C, which it equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality, very much resembles our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If this were not the case, the mini robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees possess to avoid the other bees, in our case, only the rotary movement, the acceleration as well as the slowing down could be used as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and with a higher energy concentrate, making their lifespan longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism must process only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don’t need a memory capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance, which Nissan estimates will make its way into mass-produced cars within the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his path.
