Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to the month of August 2007 - informs the Hungarian Central Bureau of Statistics.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry were only slightly higher than in July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was seen in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with firstly, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then, the production of shoes with a monthly increase of 2.5 percent.
The higher prices of plastics and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemicals and chemicals manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the petroleum processing (1.4 percent), electrical machinery and appliances manufacturing (0.9 percent), and a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 percent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase, ranging from 0.2 percent to 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a significant share of domestic industrial operations, prices rose 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the rise in gas prices imposed by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, it was the prices of the oil processing sector that saw the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5%), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3%).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 percent higher than the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was in the profit-on-investment initiating sectors.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the sectors of energy production and materials for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was 6.8 percent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they suffered a decrease of 3.9 percent over 12 months.
