On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among those invited to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of European legal protection and civil organisations, in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the deputy group Fidesz Popular Party, Járóka warned that in addition to the distinctions observed during the hiring, the Roma disappear from the labor market, in the first place, as a result of their low qualification.
"An overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have high school diplomas, and as a result of low-quality elementary education, only a tiny fraction has the possibility of obtaining a higher education diploma."
In addition, Járóka stressed that education as an elementary human right plays a key role when it comes to asserting other fundamental rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children means strengthening the economies of EU member states.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relations in the widest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Roma.
Indeed, the sooner a Roma child starts school, the more likely he is to become a productive member of the labour market; by the taxes paid from his income and consumption, he participates in the state budget.
"Through their European Union nationality, Roma must be assured of their right to quality education, and protected from low-quality, sectarian education." - underlined Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, a goal-oriented and action-oriented collaboration of the European Union is necessary for an immediate acceleration of the process of desegregation of schools. For this, compliance with the existing and preparing anti-discrimination directives is of paramount importance.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children must be given the opportunities that democracy provides, so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe" - demanded Járóka.
In the name of the European Year for Equal Opportunities for all, the objective of the Equal Opportunities Summit in Europe, which has been held every year since last year's summit in Berlin, is to provide a single platform to support measures to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination, both at European level and at Member State level.
