Accidents in the workplace, Napolitano: "Critical prevention"
Every day in Italy, there are 2,500 accidents at work, 3 deaths and 27 people who remain permanently disabled.
In 2007, Inail data confirmed that there were about 1,200 white deaths.
These figures show the severity of the phenomenon, which remains one of the main causes of death, and causes almost twice as many deaths as homicides.
In order to draw the attention of institutions, social forces and the media to this dramatic aspect, the Anmil is celebrating today, in all Italian provinces, the 58th National Day of Victims of Accidents at Work, which was institutionalized on the second Sunday in October.
"The disturbing data released by the Anmil, as well as the tragic events of the last few days, confirm the importance of the subject of prevention in the workplace," said the President of the Republic, Giorgio Napolitano, in a message sent to the President of the Anmil, National Association of Mutilated and Disabled Workers, Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his "sincere appreciation for the continuous associative effort in favor of prevention in the workplace, the protection of accident workers, assistance to the families of the victims and awareness of public opinion".
"Naturally indignant, everyone has struck their fist to put an end to such tragedies that, by their dimension, arouse the clamor of the media and the participation of public opinion, even if the daily reality presents us with dramatic cases, even repetitive in their dynamics.
Napolitano does not hide that "there is certainly a resource problem: it is essential to invest in training and information"
The many initiatives promoted in the school sector are of particular importance for a more direct awareness of young people entering the world of work.
It is our duty to maintain attention to this phenomenon, not underestimate the alarm about social gravity, apply and improve legislative norms.
For his part, the president of the Chamber Gianfranco Fini stressed how "this phenomenon of white deaths constitutes an absolute social emergency, which insults the conscience of each of us, and imposes on all institutions, to make a concrete effort to end it quickly".
The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight positive trend, but that does not prevent the number of white deaths is still impressive," said later the president of the Anmil Pietro Mercandelli.
We do not want this "discount trend" to translate into a minor attention, because it is precisely when the attention relaxes that the tragedy happens.
"We believe that in general, not enough is done to counteract the phenomenon of accidents and the contrast can be achieved through multiple actions."
“According to us,” said Mercandelli, “more controls and inspections are needed, as well as more intervention on the training of workers, and this, right from the school.”
- He added- "there is still a need to make an effort in terms of communication and public awareness.
"But above all, we need a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers in the face of a phenomenon that represents a social emergency."
Mercandelli then denounced "the progressive deterioration of the conditions for safeguarding the compensation provided for the victims of work" and the "drift of assistance towards which the system is moving in recent years".
"The aim, therefore, is to give back to the worker the guarantee of insurance," he added, "so that the fate of the one who has an accident, must not depend on the spontaneity or enlargement of the legislature."
Mp3 player pointed finger, they put at risk hearing.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a statement released in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
“From this scientific report, 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable music devices, for more than an hour a day and a week, risk permanent loss of hearing.”
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones, may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
The scientists confirm that there is good reason for concern, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit this data by using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration of exposure.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for prolonged periods, risk permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This concerns 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
