The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with super glue and, in the future, step on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring barely 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to hold a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that allow to ensure the animal, a perfect adhesion.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it “gets easily detached from the wall,” said Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton School of Engineering.
WALK ON WALLS? – “This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” Liming Dai adds.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, given that carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibers like hair, which self-cleans dust during movement on a surface to ensure a perfect and constant adhesion.
Medications: never with fruit juices.
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in summer because they are refreshing and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medications, alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing according to the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society underway in Philadelphia, he raises a new alarm, putting patients at risk: just a glass of grapefruit juice and annum health.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized because it is held responsible for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antistem and neurological drugs, up to toxic levels.
It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which had given the news in a two-year newsletter, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger deriving from this mix and to pay attention to what one drinks, if one takes medicines such as, for example, Diazepam or Methadone.
According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, director of the Department of Pharmacology at the Public University of Milan, said: "These findings are generally immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies, which will have to change the information notes of the drugs if necessary.
It is always appropriate to read the illustrative papers of the medicines you are taking, and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," the expert told Ansa agency.
