Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student housing market is not experiencing a crisis
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin have to support," explains Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia design office, "in these cities, the strong demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of widespread increase has even begun for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free, unregistered, no rent limit, sub-leases.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the taxation, are necessary to calm the prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from a minimum of 650 euros (Black Stripe area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
One can save only if one goes away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a single one in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one it costs from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, it is necessary to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, in cities such as Perugia, where rents are often taken by extra-community students, there is a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities elect historic halls.
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplexes.
“A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major urban centers of Italy, but also in the cities of province,
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the great multi-salas, and the death of consumption of the mono-salas in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems to us inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we have shared a bit of a path and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar lost as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and who can tell the story of our cinema.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have mostly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romagna leads with 82 single-stage cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that confirms that the main responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the ANEC, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favor of merchants: the antecedent debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is disgraceful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 million and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to solve the situation through the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single-room cinemas in historic centers and in the periphery.
Among the regulations foreseen, there are measures of tax facilitation in favor of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the area with limited traffic, and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like", observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by implementing other measures.
However, it is obvious that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me, has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much of shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the panels blackened by dust.
Links between politician and ‘ndrangheta, arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro.
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to standardize the choices of the City Hall to the interests of the Piromalli clan."
The magistrates of the Anti-Mafia Directorate of Calabria have launched heavy accusations against the mayor and deputy mayor of Gioia Tauro, Giorgio Dal Torrione, as well as Rosario Schiavione, and the mayor of Rosarno Carlo Martelli, arrested this morning for external competition for mafia association.
The levers also for Gioacchino Piromalli, the former mediator between the clan and the public administrations, and his grandson lawyer, namesake of the boss, already convicted of association of criminals of the mafia type, as well as to pay 10 million euros.
"an affront to legal and moral standards, and above all common sense," the prosecutors wrote, the two local administrations had expressed the willingness to pay for consultations to Master Piromalli.
