When the energy is born from the waves, now the big ones are launched.
This is an oversized deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that colossi like Chevron have set their eyes on, and now they are trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by sea swell operating systems.
That would be twice the amount that nuclear power plants produce.
And besides, there would be the currents and the tides..
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in Northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more of these companies, which have always been dedicated to traditional energy, are relying on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies," a spokesperson for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us."
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit deliberated by the American Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the United States continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, who travel the path of energy coming from the sea, and the sums invested to date, although their details are not known, indicate, according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, due to the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears of environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create a major problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
“And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the sludge up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure drives a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
Energy is sent to shore through submarine cables.
At the moment, we have four systems of this kind in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines on New York’s East River.
The movement of water during the tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that powers a generator.
Verdant announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw on energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, deserves right now, the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coasts, invested $7.5 million in 2008 and forecasts investments up to $35 million in 2009.
